# 6) In your current working directory, what does calling "git add" do? What about "git commit"? What about "git push"?
    #The git add command allows files to be included in teh next committ - it pushes things from the current working directory to the staging area. The git committ command takes things one step further and records the staged changes in the local repository. Lastly git push will push the changes from the local repository to the remote repository (GitHub)
# 7) Let's say you call "git add" in your current working directory and then "git status". What message would appear? What is it telling you?
    # Git add is a command that will add whatever files/directories you want into the staging area ready for committ, and git status will show the user the status of what is in the staging area and ready to committ.
